ation of Japan (1945–1952), the reindustrialization of Japan’s labor force during the Cold War, and the elevation of working-class foods in redefining national identity during the past two decades of economic stagnation (1990s–2000s), all contributed to the establishment of ramen as a national dish. This book is essential reading for scholars, students of Japanese history and food studies, and anyone interested in gaining greater perspective on how international policy can influence everyday foods around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aRamenzJapanxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  a20th century global history.  aamerican government.  aamerican wheat imports.  ablack market.  abowl of noodles.  acold war.  acultural studies.  aeconomic changes.  aeconomic stagnation.  afood studies.  afood.  ageopolitics.  aglobalization.  agovernment documents.  ahistorical.  ahistory.  aindustrialization.  ainternational icon.  ainternational symbol.  ajapan.  ajapanese cuisine.  ajapanese culture.  ajapanese food.  alabor force.  anational identity.  anoodle soup.  aoccupied japan.  apolitical changes.  aramen.  areindustrialization.  asoup.  aus occupation of japan.  aworking poor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027756440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095837140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958371423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958371/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY